<DocsLayout title="Secrets" description="OS-mediated secret resolution. API keys never enter LLM context.">
    <p class="lead">API keys never enter LLM context. The OS resolves them at runtime and injects them into provider connections.</p>

    <h2>The problem</h2>
    <p>
      LLM agents need API keys to call providers. But keys in environment variables, dotfiles,
      or config files leak into context windows, audit logs, and agent memory. One careless
      <code>env</code> call and your keys are in the training data.
    </p>
    <p>
      ostk solves this with OS-mediated secret resolution: the kernel resolves keys at the
      Rust process level, injects them into HTTP connections, and never exposes them to the
      LLM context or agent tooling.
    </p>

    <h2>Commands</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Command</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>ostk secret set KEY</code></td><td>Store a key in your platform keychain. Prompts interactively — value never appears in shell history.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk secret set KEY --value VAL</code></td><td>Store non-interactively (CI, scripts). Use with caution — value visible in process list.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk secret get KEY</code></td><td>Retrieve to stdout only. For subprocess injection — never prints to logs.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk secret list</code></td><td>Show which keys are available. Names only — never values.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk secret env KEY</code></td><td>Print an <code>export</code> statement for your current shell.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Resolution order</h2>
    <p>When the kernel needs a secret, it resolves in this order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>BYO secret manager</strong> — if <code>OSTK_SECRET_CMD</code> is set, the kernel calls
        your tool with the key name as argument. Works with <code>bw</code> (Bitwarden), <code>op</code> (1Password),
        <code>pass</code>, or any tool that prints the value to stdout.
        <pre><code># Example: use 1Password CLI
export OSTK_SECRET_CMD="op read op://Dev/{}"</code></pre>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Platform keychain</strong> — macOS Keychain (<code>security</code>) or Linux secret-tool.
        This is where <code>ostk secret set</code> stores keys.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Environment variable</strong> — fallback to <code>$KEY</code> in your shell environment.
        Works but less secure — env vars can leak into child processes.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Authorization</h2>
    <p>
      Having a key in your keychain is not enough. The key must also be <strong>authorized</strong>
      in your HUMANFILE's <code>SECRET</code> block:
    </p>
    <pre><code># In your HUMANFILE
SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
GEMINI_API_KEY
MISTRAL_API_KEY
KEYS</code></pre>
    <p>
      If a key isn't listed in <code>SECRET</code>, agents cannot access it — even if it exists
      in your keychain. This is the authorization boundary. The kernel enforces it at
      resolution time.
    </p>

    <h2>Provider mapping</h2>
    <p>The kernel auto-detects which key to use based on the model name in your HUMANFILE:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Model prefix</th><th>Required key</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>claude-*</code></td><td><code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>gemini-*</code></td><td><code>GEMINI_API_KEY</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>mistral-*</code> / <code>codestral-*</code></td><td><code>MISTRAL_API_KEY</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>openrouter/*</code></td><td><code>OPENROUTER_API_KEY</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>gpt-*</code> / <code>o1-*</code> / <code>o3-*</code></td><td><code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code></td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>You only need the key(s) for providers you actually use.</p>

    <h2>Quick start</h2>
    <pre><code># Store your key (interactive prompt, hidden input)
ostk secret set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY

# Verify it's stored
ostk secret list

# Authorize it in your HUMANFILE
# (ostk init --guided does this for you)

# That's it — agents resolve keys automatically</code></pre>

    <h2>Security properties</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Keys never enter LLM context</strong> — resolved at the Rust process level, injected into HTTP headers</li>
      <li><strong>Keys never appear in audit logs</strong> — only key names are logged, never values</li>
      <li><strong>Keys never appear in shell history</strong> — interactive prompt uses <code>read -s</code> with echo disabled</li>
      <li><strong>Keys never pass through agent tools</strong> — no Bash <code>env</code> or <code>printenv</code> can reach them</li>
      <li><strong>Dual authorization</strong> — key must exist in keychain AND be listed in HUMANFILE <code>SECRET</code> block</li>
      <li><strong>Timeout protection</strong> — interactive prompt times out after 30 seconds to prevent hangs</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Agentfile integration</h2>
    <p>
      Agents declared in Agentfiles can request secrets via <code>--env-passthrough</code>.
      The kernel checks the HUMANFILE <code>SECRET</code> authorization before injecting.
      Absent or unauthorized keys are denied — the agent runs without them.
    </p>

